<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,1194,2013]" box="[199,1155,1302,1329]" pageId="15" pageNumber="292">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1302,1328]" pageId="15" pageNumber="292">Description.</emphasis>
Male (
<figureCitation box="[424,532,1303,1329]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1561,1585]" captionTargetBox="[179,1411,190,1526]" captionTargetId="figure-26@16.[164,1424,181,1537]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 14. Habitus of Hexarhopalus (L.) xuhaoi sp. nov. A. Male; B. Female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4440956" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4440956/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="292">Figs 14A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[543,629,1302,1329]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1317,1341]" captionTargetBox="[156,1431,286,1289]" captionTargetId="figure-41@17.[151,1436,273,1294]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 15. Diagnostic features of Hexarhopalus (L.) xuhaoi sp. nov. (A–G. Male; H–I. Female). A. Head and pronotum, in dorsal view; B. Antenna; C. Aedeagus, ventral view; D. Same, lateral view; E. Same, dorsal view; F. Spiculum gastrale; G. Abdominal ventrite VIII of male; H. Ventrite VIII of female and spiculum; I. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4440960" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4440960/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="292">
15A 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[591,605,1303,1329]" pageId="15" pageNumber="292">–</emphasis>
G
</figureCitation>
). Body elongate, black, convex and dull-shiny.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,1194,2013]" pageId="15" pageNumber="292">
Head (
<figureCitation box="[273,374,1338,1365]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1317,1341]" captionTargetBox="[156,1431,286,1289]" captionTargetId="figure-41@17.[151,1436,273,1294]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 15. Diagnostic features of Hexarhopalus (L.) xuhaoi sp. nov. (A–G. Male; H–I. Female). A. Head and pronotum, in dorsal view; B. Antenna; C. Aedeagus, ventral view; D. Same, lateral view; E. Same, dorsal view; F. Spiculum gastrale; G. Abdominal ventrite VIII of male; H. Ventrite VIII of female and spiculum; I. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4440960" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4440960/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="292">Fig. 15A</figureCitation>
) slightly wider than long, dorsal surface crude, finely covered with short hair, punctures small. Labrum narrower than clypeus, covered with bristles of medium length in apical portion. Antennal tubercles weak, antenna (
<figureCitation box="[256,357,1410,1437]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1317,1341]" captionTargetBox="[156,1431,286,1289]" captionTargetId="figure-41@17.[151,1436,273,1294]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 15. Diagnostic features of Hexarhopalus (L.) xuhaoi sp. nov. (A–G. Male; H–I. Female). A. Head and pronotum, in dorsal view; B. Antenna; C. Aedeagus, ventral view; D. Same, lateral view; E. Same, dorsal view; F. Spiculum gastrale; G. Abdominal ventrite VIII of male; H. Ventrite VIII of female and spiculum; I. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4440960" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4440960/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="292">Fig. 15B</figureCitation>
) shorter than the combined length of head and pronotum, clubs loosely formed by apical four antennomeres. Antennomere I slightly expanded; II shortest, longer than wide; III longest, about twice as long as II, IV-VII similar, shorter than III, apical four dark brown, expanded, XI with rounded apex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,1194,2013]" pageId="15" pageNumber="292">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[325,426,1518,1545]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1317,1341]" captionTargetBox="[156,1431,286,1289]" captionTargetId="figure-41@17.[151,1436,273,1294]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 15. Diagnostic features of Hexarhopalus (L.) xuhaoi sp. nov. (A–G. Male; H–I. Female). A. Head and pronotum, in dorsal view; B. Antenna; C. Aedeagus, ventral view; D. Same, lateral view; E. Same, dorsal view; F. Spiculum gastrale; G. Abdominal ventrite VIII of male; H. Ventrite VIII of female and spiculum; I. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4440960" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4440960/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="292">Fig. 15A</figureCitation>
) about as long as wide, widest near middle, dorsal surface crude, with shallow and mussy wrinkles, and covered with small and sparse punctures and much short hairs. Groove of pronotum deep at base, the back angle oblique indentation slightly short, deep, curved forward and upward, much wide, shallow and not obvious at lateral part, median line not obvious.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,1194,2013]" pageId="15" pageNumber="292">Elytra about 2.5 times as long as wide, widest at apical 1/3, shoulders strong, Disc with regular rows of orderly longilineal punctures, and covered with irregular rows of small tubercles. Scutellum transverse, near triangular. Hind wings fully developed.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,1194,2013]" pageId="15" pageNumber="292">Femora slightly expanded, all tibiae covered with brown setae at apex, protibiae slightly curved and without modification, mesotibiae slightly curved, metatibiae straight.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,1194,2013]" pageId="15" pageNumber="292">
Aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[325,409,1842,1869]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1317,1341]" captionTargetBox="[156,1431,286,1289]" captionTargetId="figure-41@17.[151,1436,273,1294]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 15. Diagnostic features of Hexarhopalus (L.) xuhaoi sp. nov. (A–G. Male; H–I. Female). A. Head and pronotum, in dorsal view; B. Antenna; C. Aedeagus, ventral view; D. Same, lateral view; E. Same, dorsal view; F. Spiculum gastrale; G. Abdominal ventrite VIII of male; H. Ventrite VIII of female and spiculum; I. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4440960" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4440960/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="292">Figs 15</figureCitation>
C–E), near symmetrical, abdominal ventrite VIII (
<figureCitation box="[977,1079,1842,1869]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1317,1341]" captionTargetBox="[156,1431,286,1289]" captionTargetId="figure-41@17.[151,1436,273,1294]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 15. Diagnostic features of Hexarhopalus (L.) xuhaoi sp. nov. (A–G. Male; H–I. Female). A. Head and pronotum, in dorsal view; B. Antenna; C. Aedeagus, ventral view; D. Same, lateral view; E. Same, dorsal view; F. Spiculum gastrale; G. Abdominal ventrite VIII of male; H. Ventrite VIII of female and spiculum; I. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4440960" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4440960/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="292">Fig. 15G</figureCitation>
) deeply split medially at posterior margin and with long dense hair at hind margin. Spiculum gastrale (
