<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1631,2018]" pageId="16" pageNumber="293">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,438,1811,1837]" pageId="16" pageNumber="293">Comparative Notes.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Jiang &amp; Bai &amp; Ren &amp; Yang &amp; Wang, 2020" authorityName="Jiang &amp; Bai &amp; Ren &amp; Yang &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2020" box="[446,854,1811,1838]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Hexarhopalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="293" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xuhaoi" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Leprocaulus">
<emphasis box="[446,604,1811,1837]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="293">Hexarhopalus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[622,761,1811,1837]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="293">Leprocaulus</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[778,854,1811,1837]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="293">xuhaoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[862,950,1812,1838]" pageId="16" pageNumber="293" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
can be easily separated from its congeners by the following characters: shallow wrinkles on pronotum; groove of pronotum vanishing anteriorly and laterally; and femora expanded weakly. The new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Ren &amp; Xu, 2011" authorityName=", Ren &amp; xu" authorityYear="2011" box="[822,1376,1883,1910]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Hexarhopalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="293" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xui" subGenus="Leprocaulus">
<emphasis box="[822,980,1883,1909]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="293">Hexarhopalus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[996,1135,1883,1909]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="293">Leprocaulus</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[1151,1185,1884,1909]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="293">xui</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Ren, G. - D. &amp; Xu, J. - S." box="[1192,1376,1883,1910]" pageId="16" pageNumber="293" pagination="23 - 34" refId="ref11188" refString="Ren, G. - D. &amp; Xu, J. - S. (2011) The genus Hexarhopalus Fairmaire, 1891 in China, with description of three new species (Coleoptera, Tenebrionidae, Cnodalonini), Acta Zoologica Academiae Scientiarum Hungaricae, 57, 23 - 34." type="journal article" year="2011">Ren &amp; Xu, 2011</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="22.[151,250,1872,1896]" captionTargetBox="[210,1371,351,1840]" captionTargetId="figure-58@22.[201,1386,345,1848]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 20. Types of Chinese Hexarhopalus species.A. Hexarhopalus (H.) mangshanicus, Ren &amp; xu, 2011, holotype, male; B. Hexarhopalus (L.) bisinuatus, Ren &amp; xu, 2011, holotype, male; C. Hexarhopalus (L.) xui, Ren &amp; xu, 2011, holotype, female; D. Hexarhopalus (H.) attenuatus (Pic, 1922), paralectotype; E. Same, in lateral view (20A–C deposited in MHBU; 20D deposited in HNHM; figs 20D–E were taken by Tamás Németh)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4440980" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4440980/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="293">Fig. 20C</figureCitation>
) in its general appearance, but can be separated by: 1) having the whole body dark black (vs. brown); 2) shallow wrinkles on pronotum; 3) smaller tubercles on elytra; 4) broader ventrite VIII of females; 5) spiculum narrow at base; 6) elytral punctures longilineal and orderly.
</paragraph>
